<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
A large brown to reddish brown species (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 3, 4" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 3, 4.. Senaspis species, habitus, lateral view 3 S. elliotii Austen (♂) 4 S. flaviceps Macquart (♂)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures3-4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486698" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">4</figureCitation>
) differentiated from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Senaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Senaspis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Senaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by conspicuous yellow face and frons (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 24–27" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 24 - 27. Head, frontal and lateral view S. flaviceps Macquart (24, 25 ♂ 26, 27 ♀)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures24-27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486706" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">24</figureCitation>
) (dark in all other species), and a bare katepimeron (pilose in all other species). The male metafemur bears a prominent basoventral tubercle (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 80–85" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 80 - 85. Senaspis species, hind leg, anterior view 80 S. dentipes (Macquart) (♂) 81 S. dibapha (Walker) (♂) 82 S. elliotii Austen (♂) 83 S. flaviceps Macquart (♂) 84 S. flaviceps Macquart (♀) 85 S. haemorrhoa (Gerstaecker) (♂)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures80-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486720" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">83</figureCitation>
) (absent in all other species).
</paragraph>
