<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">57</emphasis>
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. haemorrhoa" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="haemorrhoa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. haemorrhoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gerstaecker) (♂) 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">58</emphasis>
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. melanthysana" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="melanthysana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. melanthysana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Speiser) (♂) 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">59</emphasis>
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. nigrita" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="nigrita">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. nigrita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Bigot) (♂).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Legs</emphasis>
. Brown to black-brown, femora partly more reddish brown ventrally; with short black pile, along posterior margin of pro- and mesofemora with longer pile. Metaleg (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 80–85" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 80 - 85. Senaspis species, hind leg, anterior view 80 S. dentipes (Macquart) (♂) 81 S. dibapha (Walker) (♂) 82 S. elliotii Austen (♂) 83 S. flaviceps Macquart (♂) 84 S. flaviceps Macquart (♀) 85 S. haemorrhoa (Gerstaecker) (♂)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures80-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486720" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">83</figureCitation>
), femur distinctly thickened, with one distinct ventral tubercle in basal fourth to fifth, tubercle with distinct short dark pile; tibia thickened, distinctly bent at base, and only slightly curved, no longer pile along ventral margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Wing</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 68–73" captionStartId="F21" captionText="Figures 68 - 73. Senaspis species, right wing 68 S. elliotii Austen (♂) 69 - 71 S. elliotii Austen close-up apical end 72 S. flaviceps Macquart (♂) 73 S. haemorrhoa (Gerstaecker) (♂)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures68-73" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486717" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">72</figureCitation>
). Yellowish brown tinge especially in anterior half, in parts more black-brown; towards posterior margin and apex more hyaline. Calypters black with fringe of silvery white pile. Cell r1 closed, petiole at least as long as height of base of stigma. Vein R4+5 sinuate but not appendiculate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Abdomen</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 91–96" captionStartId="F26" captionText="Figures 91 - 96. Senaspis species, abdomen, dorsal view 91 S. dentipes (Macquart) (♂) 92 S. dibapha (Walker) (♂) 93 S. elliotii Austen (♂) 94 S. flaviceps Macquart (♂) 95 S. haemorrhoa (Gerstaecker) (♂) 96 S. melanthysana (Speiser) (♂)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures91-96" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486722" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">94</figureCitation>
). Uniformly subshiny brown to reddish brown, terga IV and V and postabdomen often more rufous; with short dark pile, except tergum I where grey, and postabdomen where more rufous. Sterna dark; with long pale pile. Male genitalia as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 102–113" captionStartId="F28" captionText="Figures 102 - 113. Senaspis species, male terminalia 102 - 108, 110, 112 dorsal view 109, 111, 113 lateral view 102 S. dentipes (Macquart) 103 S. dibapha (Walker) 104 S. elliotii Austen 105 S. flaviceps Macquart 106 S. haemorrhoa (Gerstaecker) 107 S. nigrita (Bigot) 108, 109 S. melanthysana (Speiser) 110, 111 S. umbrifera (Walker) (holotype) 112, 113 S. nr umbrifera (Walker)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures102-113" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486724" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">105</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Female.</emphasis>
As male except for the following character states: Eye dichoptic (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 24–27" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 24 - 27. Head, frontal and lateral view S. flaviceps Macquart (24, 25 ♂ 26, 27 ♀)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures24-27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486706" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 24–27" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 24 - 27. Head, frontal and lateral view S. flaviceps Macquart (24, 25 ♂ 26, 27 ♀)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures24-27" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486706" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">27</figureCitation>
), facets of equal size. Thorax pilosity darker medially. Metafemur (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 80–85" captionStartId="F24" captionText="Figures 80 - 85. Senaspis species, hind leg, anterior view 80 S. dentipes (Macquart) (♂) 81 S. dibapha (Walker) (♂) 82 S. elliotii Austen (♂) 83 S. flaviceps Macquart (♂) 84 S. flaviceps Macquart (♀) 85 S. haemorrhoa (Gerstaecker) (♂)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1003.56557.figures80-85" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/486720" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">84</figureCitation>
) more slender, without ventral tubercle. Abdominal sterna IV-V with shorter dark pile.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
Species described from Madagascar. 
<bibRefCitation author="Keiser, F" journalOrPublisher="Verhandlungen der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Basel" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" pagination="223 - 318" refId="B34" refString="Keiser, F, 1971. Syrphidae von Madagascar (Dipt.). Verhandlungen der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Basel 81: 223 - 318" title="Syrphidae von Madagascar (Dipt.)." volume="81" year="1971">Keiser (1971)</bibRefCitation>
also reported the species from the Comoros (Grande Comore).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
The type material of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. flaviceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="flaviceps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. flaviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. apophysata" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="apophysata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. apophysata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was compared and considered to be conspecific. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1915" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Senaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Senaspis apophysata" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apophysata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Senaspis apophysata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is thus considered as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. flaviceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="flaviceps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. flaviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This synonymy was already suggested (
<bibRefCitation author="Ssymank, A" journalOrPublisher="Jahrbuch des nassauischen Vereins fuer Naturkunde" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" refId="B50" refString="Ssymank, A, Jordaens, K, De Meyer, M, Reemer, M, Rotheray, GE, in press. Syrphidae (Flower Flies or Hoverflies). In: Kirk-Spriggs A (Ed.) Manual of Afrotropical Diptera. SANBI, Pretoria." title="Syrphidae (Flower Flies or Hoverflies). In: Kirk-Spriggs A (Ed.) Manual of Afrotropical Diptera. SANBI, Pretoria." year="in press">Ssymank et al. in press</bibRefCitation>
, F.C. Thompson pers. comm.) but not formally published. The original description of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. flaviceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" rank="species" species="flaviceps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">S. flaviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mentions the type locality as &quot;De 
<normalizedToken originalValue="l’Afrique">l'Afrique</normalizedToken>
. Cap?&quot; but the type specimen bears a label indicating 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Madagascar”">&quot;Madagascar&quot;</normalizedToken>
// &quot;Goudot 1839&quot;. All studied material originates from Madagascar and no specimens collected on the African mainland were found. We, therefore, consider the current distribution of this species to be limited to Madagascar (and possibly Comoros; see 
<bibRefCitation author="Keiser, F" journalOrPublisher="Verhandlungen der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Basel" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" pagination="223 - 318" refId="B34" refString="Keiser, F, 1971. Syrphidae von Madagascar (Dipt.). Verhandlungen der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Basel 81: 223 - 318" title="Syrphidae von Madagascar (Dipt.)." volume="81" year="1971">Keiser 1971</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Senaspis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Senaspis flaviceps" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flaviceps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Senaspis flaviceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all other species within the genus in some aspects, such as the bare katepimeron (pilose in the rest, albeit weakly so), the presence of a basal tubercle in the male metafemur (absent in all others), the relatively longer petiole (at least as long as height of base of stigma, shorter in all others), and the larger body size (larger than 17 mm and up to 23 mm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
